<div class="prose">
  <h1>Projects</h1>
  <p>
    One question — <em>what does it take to be?</em> — pursued at the
    smallest honest scale we can build and hold in a hand.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="projects">
  <article class="project">
    <h3>being.0 <span class="tag">embodiment</span></h3>
    <p>
      The floor of the question, made physical. A palm-sized creature on a
      single ~$15 chip: solar panels that are its food and its eyes at once,
      a strip of light for its state, a hunger it has to answer. We gave it
      no rule for finding the light — it had to <em>learn</em> to, from its
      own experience of going hungry, and it now runs that learned self
      faithfully on the chip. What is the least it takes for something to
      <em>be</em>?
    </p>
    <p class="more">
      <a href="/notes/2026-05-29-learning-the-light/">Learning the light →</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</div>

<div class="prose" style="margin-top:2.5rem">
  <h2>Lineage</h2>
  <p>
    The aesthetic owes more to Stanisław Lem than to any AI lab: machines
    worth taking seriously as beings, built and described with rigour and
    affection. The methods borrow from how nervous systems actually
    work — perception, drives, rest, consolidation — rather than from the
    usual vocabulary of the field.
  </p>
</div>
